SIMPLE: sprig
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sprig
<hw>Sprig</hw> <pr>(spr⟦icr⟧g)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>sprec</ets>; akin to Icel. <ets>sprek</ets> a stick. Cf.
<er>Spray</er> a branch.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A small shoot or twig
of a tree or other plant; a spray; <as>as, a <ex>sprig</ex> of laurel or
of parsley</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A youth; a lad; -- used humorously or in slight
disparagement.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>sprig</qex> whom I remember, with a whey-face and a
satchel, not so many years ago.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A brad, or nail without a head.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A small eyebolt ragged or barbed
at the point.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sprig</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sprig
<hw>Sprig</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Sprigged</conjf> <pr>(spr⟦icr⟧gd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Sprigging</conjf> <pr>(-g⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>.]</vmorph>
<def>To mark or adorn with the representation of small branches; to work
with sprigs; <as>as, to <ex>sprig</ex> muslin</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sprigged</ent>⟦br⟧
